parameters:
The room ahead must be where the guards are. We shouldn't
carelessly enter without a reason.

If Akane's information is accurate, then there are fewer
guards here compared to the number of laborers on site.

Therefore, to prevent a numerically advantageous rebellion,
the guards' sleeping hours are basically when work here also
stops.

However, it's not completely halted. A small number of
workers are still made to work at night, under the
supervision of a few guards.

The exact distance and structure from here to the exit is
unknown. But considering that the crystal traders have been
seen, it's predicted that the exit isn't too far away.

The strict iron bars may also be a strategy considering the
possibility that someone could escape or reach the distance.

Still, it's not hard to imagine that we'll have to
forcefully break through the guards' surveillance at some
point.

The patrol is thin. The guards' eyes are on the workers.
Therefore, it wouldn't be impossible to strike from the
darkness and silence them in one blow.

I'll take care of clearing the way. Akane, you just focus on
unlocking the door as you were.
Akane: It's not much of a plan, but I've got the gist of it.

Akane: Now that we know, let's say goodbye to this place
quickly!

Akane: Hey you! You're not thinking of doing something
stupid, are you?!

Akane: How long do you think it's going to take to unlock
all these cells for these guys?!

Akane: And after freeing them, do you really think those
spineless fools have the guts to escape with us?!

Akane: Leading a bunch of dead weights who don't have the
energy or strength to rebel against the guards, there's no
way we can escape from here! Get a grip, will you?!

Akane: If you can't leave them behind, then after the two of
us escape, we can come back and save them! Until then,
well... they might have to endure some tough days...

Akane: But think about the people who'd be dragged into your
reckless ideal of an escape without knowing what dangers lie
ahead!
Akane: Hey! Are you listening to me?!
Section Chief: Remember this one thing.

Section Chief: Here, you think about yourself, only yourself,
first and foremost.

Section Chief: That's for your own good, and for the good of
others too.

Section Chief: Make sure you engrave this in your mind, especially
someone naive and overly serious like you.
(If I were to only think of myself...)

(I could have pushed the blame for the collapse accident
onto a single "naive and overly serious" newcomer who
doesn't know left from right...)
(And yet, here I am, standing like this...)

Of course, Akane's thinking is correct. I understand that
I'm saying something foolish, and I'm aware that this can't
be done without your cooperation.

Even if we manage to escape on our own, the guards will
surely pin the blame on the workers. And I can imagine what
would happen as a result...

Therefore, I at least want to give them a choice. I want to
gather those who wish to escape with us.

This is my selfishness. I don't want to lie, not about my
own feelings.
I'll be a nuisance. But still, I want to ask...

Akane: Ahh, come on! You really have no intention of
reconsidering, do you!?

Akane: It's a done deal! If we're going to do this, I'll see
it through to the end!!

Akane: But you're on your own with this escape game with
your friends! I can't stand out by unlocking doors with a
group in tow. I'll head to the exit first!
I'm sorry. I'm in your debt.

Akane: Hmph! I've had my fair share of rough treatment from
the guards here too. I think it's only fair to make them
foam at the mouth a little!

Akane: But since I'm indulging your whims, you better
protect my life even if it kills you! Once we reach the
royal capital, you better prepare a hefty reward! That's a
promise, got it!?
Yes! I swear on my chivalry to keep that promise!
